{"title_page": "Elles (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2011 film by Ma\u0142gorzata Szumowska}}\n{{distinguish|Elle (film)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Elles\n| image = Elles2011Poster.jpg\n| caption = Film poster\n| director = [[Ma\u0142goska Szumowska]] <!-- name per film's credits and some versions of the poster: http://www.impawards.com/intl/misc/2012/elles_ver4_xlg.html (in other versions of the poster she is credited as \u201cMalgoska Szumowska\u201d) -->\n| starring = {{plainlist |\n* [[Juliette Binoche]]\n* [[Ana\u00efs Demoustier]]\n* [[Joanna Kulig]]\n}}\n| producer = [[Marianne Slot]]\n| writer = {{plainlist |\n* [[Tine Byrckel]]\n* Ma\u0142goska Szumowska <!-- Byrckel is first billed in the credits -->\n}}\n| released = {{Film date|df=y|2011|9|9|[[Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2012|2|1|France|2012|2|17|Poland|2012|3|29|Germany}}\n| music          = [[Pawe\u0142 Mykietyn]]\n| cinematography = Micha\u0142 Englert \n| editing        = Fran\u00e7oise Tourmen<br>Jacek Drosio\n| country = {{plainlist |\n* France\n* Poland\n* Germany\n}}\n| language = {{plainlist |\n* French\n* Polish\n}}\n| runtime = 92 minutes\n| distributor = [[Memento Films]]\n| budget = $4 million <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=12467|title=Elles (2012) (2012) - JPBox-Office|website=www.jpbox-office.com}}</ref>\n| gross = $3.8 million <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=elles.htm|title=Elles (2012) - International Box Office Results - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Elles''''' is a 2011 European film, directed and co-written by Polish director [[Ma\u0142goska Szumowska]]. It shows an episode in the life of Anne ([[Juliette Binoche]]), a journalist in [[Paris, France|Paris]] for French [[Elle (magazine)|''Elle'']] who is writing an article about female student [[prostitution]].\n\nAlthough the young women are not keen on publicity, she persuades two students to talk to her: the provocative Alicja ([[Joanna Kulig]]), an ambitious economics student who left Poland to further her education; and the subtle Charlotte ([[Ana\u00efs Demoustier]]), enrolled in a Parisian ''classe pr\u00e9paratoire'', determined to leave her modest provincial background behind.\n\nWhere Anne is expecting misery and distress, she discovers freedom, pride, and empowerment. As Anne's professional curiosity in the two women becomes a matter of personal interest, she starts to rediscover her own sexuality.\n\n''Elles'' premiered at the [[2011 Toronto International Film Festival]] and first entered general release in France in February 2012.\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film is set during the course of one day. Anne ([[Juliette Binoche]]) is trying to meet the deadline for her article about prostitution, while shopping and preparing dinner for her husband's boss and his wife. She is also worried about her two sons, the eldest of whom has been skipping classes while the younger appears to start being hooked on video games. This narrative is interrupted by the flashbacks to the conversations Anne has had with the two students, scenes from their lives, and the effect that their work in the sex industry is having on them and those close to them.\n\nAnne interviews Alicja ([[Joanna Kulig]]), arriving from Poland to study in France, she not only lost her suitcase but found the student advisors to be less than helpful in her hour of need. Another student came to her rescue, but admitted that his generosity was part of the courtship. By the time we see her being interviewed by Anne, Alicja has earned enough to have a very nice apartment along with designer clothes and handbags. She is much more hedonistic than Charlotte and proceeds to get Anne drunk during the course of the interview in her apartment. When asked who her clients are, Alicja simply replies that they are bored husbands. For Alicja, being alone in a foreign country has led her to seemingly much more freedom than she enjoyed at home, but when asked if she wanted to stop, she admits that there is an element of addiction with the way she earns money. \n\nCharlotte ([[Ana\u00efs Demoustier]]) is quite a different person, she seems very relaxed about the sex she has with her clients. She has tried doing part-time work but found that her studies suffered so she turned to prostitution. But she still does the occasional shift as she needs to be able to explain to her family and boyfriend where the money comes from. These sexual encounters inevitably lead to conflict in her relationship with her boyfriend who at one point demands to know if she is seeing someone else. Her friendly, girl-next-door nature leads her clients to confide in her about their lives \u2013 their jobs, their wives \u2013 which has surprised Charlotte as she had imagined the work would have been non-stop sex. \n\nHow the students' lives turn out is left to the viewer to decide, with the end of the film focusing more on Anne's life and the effect these encounters with the two students have had on her and her relationship with her husband.\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Malgoska Szumowska Juliette Binoche 2012.jpg|thumb|right|Ma\u0142gorzata Szumowska and Juliette Binoche at the film premiere.]]\n\n* [[Juliette Binoche]] as Anne\n* [[Ana\u00efs Demoustier]] as Charlotte\n* [[Joanna Kulig]] as Alicja\n* [[Krystyna Janda]] as Alicja's mother\n* [[Louis-Do de Lencquesaing]] as Patrick\n* [[Andrzej Chyra]] as Sadist client\n* [[Ali Marhyar]] as Sa\u00efd\n* [[Jean-Marie Binoche]] as Anne's father\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois Civil]] as Florent (Anne and Patrick's older son)\n* [[Pablo Beugnet]] as St\u00e9phane (Anne and Patrick's younger son)\n* {{ill|Val\u00e9rie Dr\u00e9ville|fr}} as Charlotte's mother\n* {{ill|Jean-Louis Coulloc'h|fr}} as Charlotte's father\n* [[Arthur Moncia]] as Thomas\n* [[Scali Delpeyrat]] as Charles\n* [[Laurence Ragon]] as Colette\n* [[Alain Libolt]] as Colette's husband\n* [[Florence Loiret Caille]] as Rita\n* [[Swann Arlaud]] as Young client\n* [[Nicolas Layani]] as Guitar client\n\n==MPAA rating==\nThe film was originally rated NC-17 in the US as a result of explicit sexual content,<ref>{{cite web|title=Elles|publisher=The New York Times|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2012/04/27/movies/elles-with-juliette-binoche-about-prostitution.html|accessdate=December 15, 2012}}</ref> but this rating was later surrendered<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmratings.com/Search?filmTitle=elles&x=16&y=4|title=Elles-Filmratings|date=20 May 2018|website=MPAA|access-date=20 May 2018}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of French films]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1549589|Elles}}\n\n\n[[Category:2011 films]]\n[[Category:German films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:2010s erotic films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Paris]]\n[[Category:French independent films]]\n[[Category:Polish films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Polish-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Cologne (Germany)]]\n[[Category:German independent films]]\n[[Category:French erotic films]]\n[[Category:French multilingual films]]\n[[Category:Polish multilingual films]]\n[[Category:German erotic films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ma\u0142gorzata Szumowska]]\n[[Category:Films about prostitution in Paris]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2011 film by Ma\u0142gorzata Szumowska}}\n{{distinguish|Elle (film)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Elles\n| image = Elles2011Poster.jpg\n| caption = Film poster\n| director = [[Ma\u0142goska Szumowska]] <!-- name per film's credits and some versions of the poster: http://www.impawards.com/intl/misc/2012/elles_ver4_xlg.html (in other versions of the poster she is credited as \u201cMalgoska Szumowska\u201d) -->\n| starring = {{plainlist |\n* [[Juliette Binoche]]\n* [[Ana\u00efs Demoustier]]\n* [[Joanna Kulig]]\n}}\n| producer = [[Marianne Slot]]\n| writer = {{plainlist |\n* [[Tine Byrckel]]\n* Ma\u0142goska Szumowska <!-- Byrckel is first billed in the credits -->\n}}\n| released = {{Film date|df=y|2011|9|9|[[Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2012|2|1|France|2012|2|17|Poland|2012|3|29|Germany}}\n| music          = [[Pawe\u0142 Mykietyn]]\n| cinematography = Micha\u0142 Englert \n| editing        = Fran\u00e7oise Tourmen<br>Jacek Drosio\n| country = {{plainlist |\n* France\n* Poland\n* Germany\n}}\n| language = {{plainlist |\n* French\n* Polish\n}}\n| runtime = 92 minutes\n| distributor = [[Memento Films]]\n| budget = $4 million <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=12467|title=Elles (2012) (2012) - JPBox-Office|website=www.jpbox-office.com}}</ref>\n| gross = $3.8 million <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=elles.htm|title=Elles (2012) - International Box Office Results - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Elles''''' is a 2011 European film, directed and co-written by Polish director [[Ma\u0142goska Szumowska]]. It shows an episode in the life of Anne ([[Juliette Binoche]]), a journalist in [[Paris, France|Paris]] for French [[Elle (magazine)|''Elle'']] who is writing an article about female student [[prostitution]].\n\nAlthough the young women are not keen on publicity, she persuades two students to talk to her: the provocative Alicja ([[Joanna Kulig]]), an ambitious economics student who left Poland to further her education; and the subtle Charlotte ([[Ana\u00efs Demoustier]]), enrolled in a Parisian ''classe pr\u00e9paratoire'', determined to leave her modest provincial background behind.\n\nWhere Anne is expecting misery and distress, she discovers freedom, pride, and empowerment. As Anne\u2019s professional curiosity in the two women becomes a matter of personal interest, she starts to rediscover her own sexuality.\n\n''Elles'' premiered at the [[2011 Toronto International Film Festival]] and first entered general release in France in February 2012.\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film is set during the course of one day. Anne ([[Juliette Binoche]]) is trying to meet the deadline for her article about prostitution, while shopping and preparing dinner for her husband's boss and his wife. She is also worried about her two sons, the eldest of whom has been skipping classes while the younger appears to start being hooked on video games. This narrative is interrupted by the flashbacks to the conversations Anne has had with the two students, scenes from their lives, and the effect that their work in the sex industry is having on them and those close to them.\n\nAnne interviews Alicja ([[Joanna Kulig]]), arriving from Poland to study in France, she not only lost her suitcase but found the student advisors to be less than helpful in her hour of need. Another student came to her rescue, but admitted that his generosity was part of the courtship. By the time we see her being interviewed by Anne, Alicja has earned enough to have a very nice apartment along with designer clothes and handbags. She is much more hedonistic than Charlotte and proceeds to get Anne drunk during the course of the interview in her apartment. When asked who her clients are, Alicja simply replies that they are bored husbands. For Alicja, being alone in a foreign country has led her to seemingly much more freedom than she enjoyed at home, but when asked if she wanted to stop, she admits that there is an element of addiction with the way she earns money. \n\nCharlotte ([[Ana\u00efs Demoustier]]) is quite a different person, she seems very relaxed about the sex she has with her clients. She has tried doing part-time work but found that her studies suffered so she turned to prostitution. But she still does the occasional shift as she needs to be able to explain to her family and boyfriend where the money comes from. These sexual encounters inevitably lead to conflict in her relationship with her boyfriend who at one point demands to know if she is seeing someone else. Her friendly, girl-next-door nature leads her clients to confide in her about their lives \u2013 their jobs, their wives \u2013 which has surprised Charlotte as she had imagined the work would have been non-stop sex. \n\nHow the students' lives turn out is left to the viewer to decide, with the end of the film focusing more on Anne's life and the effect these encounters with the two students have had on her and her relationship with her husband.\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Malgoska Szumowska Juliette Binoche 2012.jpg|thumb|right|Ma\u0142gorzata Szumowska and Juliette Binoche at the film premiere.]]\n\n* [[Juliette Binoche]] as Anne\n* [[Ana\u00efs Demoustier]] as Charlotte\n* [[Joanna Kulig]] as Alicja\n* [[Krystyna Janda]] as Alicja's mother\n* [[Louis-Do de Lencquesaing]] as Patrick\n* [[Andrzej Chyra]] as Sadist client\n* [[Ali Marhyar]] as Sa\u00efd\n* [[Jean-Marie Binoche]] as Anne's father\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois Civil]] as Florent (Anne and Patrick's older son)\n* [[Pablo Beugnet]] as St\u00e9phane (Anne and Patrick's younger son)\n* {{ill|Val\u00e9rie Dr\u00e9ville|fr}} as Charlotte's mother\n* {{ill|Jean-Louis Coulloc'h|fr}} as Charlotte's father\n* [[Arthur Moncia]] as Thomas\n* [[Scali Delpeyrat]] as Charles\n* [[Laurence Ragon]] as Colette\n* [[Alain Libolt]] as Colette's husband\n* [[Florence Loiret Caille]] as Rita\n* [[Swann Arlaud]] as Young client\n* [[Nicolas Layani]] as Guitar client\n\n==MPAA rating==\nThe film was originally rated NC-17 in the US as a result of explicit sexual content,<ref>{{cite web|title=Elles|publisher=The New York Times|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2012/04/27/movies/elles-with-juliette-binoche-about-prostitution.html|accessdate=December 15, 2012}}</ref> but this rating was later surrendered<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmratings.com/Search?filmTitle=elles&x=16&y=4|title=Elles-Filmratings|date=20 May 2018|website=MPAA|access-date=20 May 2018}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of French films]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1549589|Elle